summary: Check if there is no python call trace error when do_patch fail (auto)
author: alexandru.c.georgescu@intel.com
action:
1. Prepare yocto build environment
2. Modify a patch for one recipe and make it that it could not be applied successfully. For example, you could modify the patches for "m4-native".
In order to find the patches for "m4-native", look into: ../meta/recipes-devtools/m4/m4-native_1.4.17.bb. This will indicate you the: ../meta/recipes-devtools/m4/m4-1.4.17.inc file which leads to 2 pathces:
ac_config_links.patch -> mcedit ../meta/recipes-devtools/m4/m4/ac_config_links.patch and
remove-gets.patch -> mcedit ../meta/recipes-devtools/m4/m4/remove-gets.patch
3. Run "bitbake m4-native -c patch"
4. bitbake should report the error of patching without python call trace
expected_results: There is no python call trace error when do_patch fail

summary: Check if bitbake-runtask command works.
author: alexandru.c.georgescu@intel.com
action:
1. Download poky source and prepare the build environment .

2. Run bitbake man

3. Run bitbake -c clean man

4. Run “bitbake-runtask” command to build some packages. For example, run the following commands:
    "bitbake-runtask man_1.6g do_fetch"
    "bitbake-runtask man_1.6g do_unpack"
    "bitbake-runtask man_1.6g do_patch"
    "bitbake-runtask man_1.6g do_configure"
    "bitbake-runtask man_1.6g do_compile"
    "bitbake-runtask man_1.6g do_install"
    "bitbake-runtask man_1.6g do_populate_lic"
    "bitbake-runtask man_1.6g do_populate_sysroot"
5. Check the return value of each command by using “echo $?”  and check the log file in work directory.
expected_results: The return value of each command should be “0” and no error message in log file.

summary: Enable PR service with remote server/local client mode
author: alexandru.c.georgescu@intel.com
action:
1. prepare 2 poky source tree (different location)

2. prepare 2 build environments from 2 different poky source tree.

3. in one of the poky source, run "bitbake-prserv --start"
4. in the second poky source, set PRSERV_HOST = "127.0.0.1:8585" in conf/local.conf
5. run "bitbake xcursor-transparent-theme" and then add following lines into xcursor-transparent-theme_${PV}.bb (/meta/recipes-graphics/xcursor-transparent-theme/xcursor-transparent-theme_git.bb)

------------------------------------------
do_package_append() {

    bb.build.exec_func('do_test_prserv', d)
}

do_test_prserv() {
    echo "Test if PR service could work"
}
---------------------------------------

6. Check the version of  "xcursor-transparent-theme" under tmp/deploy/rpm/noarch is r0.0
       - example " xcursor-transparent-theme*-r0.0.all.rpm"

7. re-run "bitbake xcursor-transparent-theme", task do_packge for recipe xcursor-transparent-theme should be re-run
8. check the xcursor-transparent-theme package built out under deploy folder, the PR number should bump up automatically
expected_results:
PR number should bump up with remote server/local client mode

example " xcursor-transparent-theme*-r0.1.all.rpm"

summary: Detect Host system changes with sstate (auto)
author: alexandru.c.georgescu@intel.com
action:
1. Run “bitbake binutils-cross binutils-native”
2. Check that a directory with your linux distribution name and version exists in /build/sstate-cache
3. Check that all sstate-binutils-native-*.tgz and sstate-binutils-cross-*.tgz packages are in this directory
4. Rename the directory (ex: Ubuntu-12.04 to Ubuntu-13.04)
5. Run "bitbake -cclean binutils-cross binutils-native" to remove the packages from the tmp/ directory
6. Run "bitbake binutils-cross binutils-native" to rebuild the packages
7. A new directory should be made in /build/sstate-cache with your linux distribution name and version
8. Check that new sstate-binutils-native-*.tgz and sstate-binutils-cross-*.tgz packages are in this directory (this means that old ones are not reused)
expected_results: Bitbake should store and only use sstate-*-native-*.tgz and sstate-*-cross-*.tgz packages from a directory with your linux distribution name and version in /build/sstate-cache (ex: /build/sstate-cache/ Ubuntu-12.04). If these are not present, they are built.

summary: event handlers are executed based on event masks (auto)
author: corneliux.stoicescu@intel.com
action:
1. create 'meta/classes/test.bbclass' with the following content:

python test1_eventhandler() {
    bb.note("Test for bb.event.BuildStarted")
}
python test2_eventhandler() {
    bb.note("Test for bb.event.BuildCompleted")
}
python test3_eventhandler() {
    bb.note("Test for bb.event.InvalidEvent")
}
addhandler test1_eventhandler
test1_eventhandler[eventmask] = "bb.event.BuildStarted"
addhandler test2_eventhandler
test2_eventhandler[eventmask] = "bb.event.BuildCompleted"
addhandler test3_eventhandler
test3_eventhandler[eventmask] = "bb.event.InvalidEvent"

2. Add in local.conf:

INHERIT += "test"

3. run 'bitbake m4-native'
expected_results:
Analize bitbake's output as follows:
1. look for "NOTE: Test for bb.event.BuildStarted" at the start of the build
2. look for "NOTE: Test for bb.event.BuildCompleted" when the build finishes
3. there should be no message "NOTE: Test for bb.event.InvalidEvent"

summary: Avoid cache reload for incremental development using a backgrounded bitbake server
author: corneliux.stoicescu@intel.com
action:
1) get poky sources (1.5 +)

NOTE: The poky source should not have an already-made 'build' directory within

2) in a fresh shell session source oe-init-build-env
3) Run "bitbake -p"
4) Run "time bitbake -e"
-- see expected results --
5) In another fresh shell session, source oe-init-build-env-memres
6) Run "bitbake -p"
7) Run "time bitbake -e"
-- see expected results --
8) close the bitbake server by issuing command: 'bitbake -m'

NOTE: Don't reuse this shell session for any further tests. Close it and continue testing in a new one.
expected_results: Compare time spent for cache loading by bitbake between steps 4) and 7) . During step 7) it should be much shorter.

summary: bitbake can use alternate download methods than git
author: stanciux.mihail@intel.com
action:
1. Start by creating a fresh build directory:
    source oe-init-build-env newbuild

2a. break the proxy settings for git by issuing the following command:
    sudo chmod -x /usr/local/bin/git-proxy

2b. or, if the proxy configuration differs, another way to do it is by executing in the same shell session:
    GIT_PROXY_COMMAND=
     Make sure that gitproxy is unset in ~/.gitconfig

3. fetch all required packages for a core-image-sato image by issuing
    bitbake core-image-sato --runall=fetch

4a. once bitbake finishes, repair the git proxy settings with:
    sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/git-proxy

4b. or, if 2b was followed, close the shell session and open a new one to refresh the environment
expected_results: bitbake command issued on step 3 should complete successfully

author: jose.perez.carranza@intel.com
action:
1. clone poky
2. cd poky  
3. source oe-init-build-env && cd build 
4. set below in local.conf 
	MACHINE = "qemux86"
5. bitbake linux-yocto -c kernel_configme -f
6. bitbake linux-yocto -c menuconfig
7. Once menuconfig launches, use the interface to navigate through the selections and
   enable option "64-bit kernel"
8. Save changes and set name of the file as "test.config"
expected_results:
8. Open file:
poky/build//tmp/work/qemux86-poky-linux/linux-yocto/4.X.X+*/linux-qemux86-standard-build/test.config
 and verify that changes are present in the file as follows: 
        
		CONFIG_64BIT=y
		CONFIG_X86_64=y

summary: test_bitbake_devshell
author: jose.perez.carranza@intel.com
action:
1. clone poky
2. cd poky  
3. source oe-init-build-env && cd build 
4. bitbake matchbox-desktop
5. bitbake matchbox-desktop -c devshell 
6. Verify that "matchbox-desktop" binary file is not created under  "src" directory
7. Run below command:
$ ./configure && make
8. Exit from the devshell terminal 
$ exit
expected_results:
4. Package was build correctly 
5. A terminal with a shell prompt within the OpenEmbedded build environment is opened 


7. Verify that "matchbox-desktop" binary file was created successfully under "src/" directory
8. Terminal back to the build directory

summary: test_dependency_explorer_is_launched
author: jose.perez.carranza@intel.com
action:
1. clone poky
2. cd poky
3. source oe-init-build-env
4. bitbake core-image-full-cmdline
5. bitbake -u taskexp -g core-image-full-cmdline

NOTE: To execute the last command of this test, it's necessary that the machine is executing an X11 server, or if that's not the case (for example, if running the test on a headless server), it is required to enable ssh X11 forwarding on both, the server and the client, and have the X11 server running on the client.

The instructions to enable X11 forwarding vary between distributions. But for example, these are the steps to enable it between a server running openSUSE Leap 42.1 and a client with Fedora 24:

1. On the server, make sure /home/<username>/.ssh/config contains the line:
    ForwardX11 yes
2. On the server, make sure xauth is installed by running:
    which xauth
3. On the client, connect to the server, enabling X11 forwarding, for example by using:
    ssh -X user@server

NOTE 2: depexp was renamed to taskexp on 2.3 M4
expected_results:
4. Image should be successfully built
5. Verify that a "dependency explorer" is opened and file 
   dependencies are listed

summary: test_bitbake_sane_error_for_invalid_layer
author: jose.perez.carranza@intel.com
action:
1. clone poky
2. cd poky  
3. source oe-init-build-env && cd build 
4. Add a invalid layer to conf/bblayers.conf 
      "<poky dir>/my-invalid-layer"
5. bitbake core-image-minimal
expected_results:
5. Below error should be displayed:
     "ERROR: Layer directory <my-invalid-layer dir> does not exist!
     Please check BBLAYERS in <poky dir>/<build dir>/conf/bblayers.conf"

summary: Test bitbake-selftest
author: jair.de.jesus.gonzalez.plascencia@intel.com
action:
1. clone poky
2. cd poky
3. source oe-init-build-env
4. bitbake-selftest -v
expected_results: 4. All test cases are executed and no errors are reported.

summary: Check if AUTOPR could be export/lockdown for package build.
author: alexandru.c.georgescu@intel.com
action:
1. prepare 2 poky build environments

2. in one of the poky source, set PRSERV_HOST to localhost and PRSERV_PORT to 0 in local.conf
4. run "bitbake man" and then add following lines into man_${PV}.bb
#######
do_package_append() {
        bb.build.exec_func('do_test_prserv', d)
}

do_test_prserv() {
 echo "Test if PR service could work"
}
#######
5. re-run "bitbake man", and check the deploy folder if the packages for man are re-generated with PR number bump up
6. run "bitbake-prserv-tool export export.inc"
7. in the second poky source, set PRSERV_HOST to localhost and PRSERV_PORT to 0 in local.conf

8. copy export.inc into the second poky source's build directory
9. run "bitbake -R export.inc man"
10. check the deploy folder if the packages for man are generated with same PR number in first poky build folder
expected_results: Check if AUTOPR could be export/lockdown for package build.

summary: Check if AUTOPR could be export/import for package build

action:
1. prepare 2 poky build environments

2. in one of the poky source, set PRSERV_HOST to localhost and PRSERV_PORT to 0 in local.conf
4. run "bitbake man" and then add following lines into man_${PV}.bb
#######
do_package_append() {
        bb.build.exec_func('do_test_prserv', d)
}

do_test_prserv() {
 echo "Test if PR service could work"
}
#######
7. re-run "bitbake man", and check the deploy folder if the packages for man are re-generated with PR number bump up
8. run "bitbake-prserv-tool export export.inc"

summary: Make sure basichash works with PR service
author: alexandru.c.georgescu@intel.com
action:
1. prepare 1 poky build environments
2. poky source, set PRSERV_HOST to localhost and PRSERV_PORT to 0 in local.conf
4. run "bitbake man"
5. check the stamps folder, note down the file name of the do_package file for man
6. add following lines into man_${PV}.bb

#######
do_package_append() {
        bb.build.exec_func('do_test_prserv', d)
}

do_test_prserv() {
 echo "Test if PR service could work"
}
#######

7. re-run "bitbake man", task do_packge for recipe man should be re-run
8. check the stamps folder, the do_package file for man should be regentered with hash value changed
expected_results: Make sure basichas works with PR service.

summary: Enable PR service with remote server/local client mode
author: alexandru.c.georgescu@intel.com
action:
1. prepare 2 poky build environments
2. in one of the poky source, run "bitbake-prserv --start"
3. in the second poky source, set PRSERV_HOST to 127.0.0.1 and PRSERV_PORT to 8585
4. run "bitbake man" and then add following lines into man_${PV}.bb


#######
do_package_append() {
        bb.build.exec_func('do_test_prserv', d)
}

do_test_prserv() {
 echo "Test if PR service could work"
}
#######


5. re-run "bitbake man", task do_packge for recipe man should be re-run
6. check the man package built out under deploy folder, the PR number should bump up automatically
expected_results: PR number should bump up with remote server/local client mode
